      "role": "user",
      "content": "got it. i'll check the injectors and fuel pressure next. regarding the vacuum leaks, is there a specific way you recommend testing for them on this engine? like a smoke machine or just soapy water?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, vacuum leaks, the sneaky little gremlins that can cause all sorts of trouble. To hunt them down, you can indeed use a smoke machine. This magical contraption will release a cloud of smoke into the intake manifold, and if there's a leak, the smoke will escape, revealing its hiding place. It's a bit like finding a hidden passage in a castle, but instead of a secret tunnel, you're looking for a gap in the engine's defenses.\n\nAlternatively, you can use soapy water. Dip a piece of wire or a thin hose into the soapy water and carefully place it near the intake manifold and vacuum lines. Watch for bubbles, which will appear if there's a leak. It's like using a potion to reveal hidden enemies in a dark forest.\n\nRemember, these methods are not foolproof, and sometimes the leaks are as elusive as a dragon's lair. But with patience and a bit of luck, you'll find them. Good luck, brave adventurer, and may your journey be free of goblin interference!",
      "source": "target",
