      "role": "user",
      "content": "huh ok. i'll try the smoke machine first. if that doesn't show anything, could it be an issue with the fuel trim values specifically? how would i interpret those to see if the lean side is bank 1 or bank 2?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, fuel trim values, the ancient runes of the engine's soul. They tell tales of the balance between air and fuel, and when they lean towards the lean side, it can indeed be a mystery worthy of a riddle from a sphinx.\n\nTo interpret these mystical numbers, you'll want to peek into the bank 1 and bank 2 fuel trim values. Bank 1 refers to the left side of the engine, while bank 2 refers to the right. If the lean side is bank 1, you'll see the fuel trim values there are too lean, meaning the engine is not getting enough fuel. If it's bank 2, then the right side is the culprit.\n\nTo read these values, you'll need to connect an OBD-II scanner to your vehicle's computer. Once connected, navigate to the fuel trim section. Look for the short-term and long-term fuel trim values for both banks. If the short-term fuel trim is consistently negative (lean), that's your lean side. A positive value would indicate a rich condition.\n\nInterpreting these values is like deciphering the language of the ancients, but once you master it, you'll be able to tune your engine to the perfect harmony of air and fuel. Good luck",
      "source": "target",
